const LORE = {

  // ── World lore ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  narmir: [
    { id:'narmir_1',  title:'The First Age',               msg:'Before the kingdoms rose, Narmir was a vast wilderness of raw magic — mountains that breathed, rivers that sang, and forests whose roots reached the core of the world. No map could hold it. No name could contain it.' },
    { id:'narmir_2',  title:'The Sundering',                msg:'The world was once whole. Then the Arch-Mages of the Third Conclave attempted to bind all magic into a single point. The resulting explosion shattered the Weave, splitting the continent into the broken landmass players now contest.' },
    { id:'narmir_3',  title:'The Weave',                    msg:'Magic in Narmir does not come from a god or a source — it comes from the Weave, an invisible lattice of energy that runs through all living things. Mages do not create magic. They listen for it, coax it, and sometimes wrestle it into submission.' },
    { id:'narmir_4',  title:'The Age of Crowns',            msg:'Following the Sundering came three hundred years of endless war as every warlord, elder, and petty chief claimed dominion over the broken land. Historians call this the Age of Crowns — not because many were worn, but because so many were taken.' },
    { id:'narmir_5',  title:'The Compact of Five',          msg:'The first lasting peace came through an unlikely alliance of five kingdoms — a dwarf stronghold, a human city-state, an elven grove, an orcish warband, and a dark elf conclave. Their treaty, hammered out over seventeen days in a neutral tavern, became the foundation of modern diplomacy.' },
    { id:'narmir_6',  title:'The Calendar of Seasons',      msg:'Narmir does not measure time in years. It measures time in Seasons — each cycle lasting thirteen days as the moons align. Spring for growth, Summer for war, Fall for harvest, Winter for survival. Every ruler learns to read the skies.' },
    { id:'narmir_7',  title:'The Dead Roads',               msg:'Beneath every major city lie the Dead Roads — ancient trade tunnels carved by the first civilisations. They still connect distant cities, but their original builders have been gone so long that no one agrees which race made them. All six races claim credit.' },
    { id:'narmir_8',  title:'The War of Salt',              msg:'The bloodiest conflict in recorded history began over a salt flat the size of a small town. Seventeen kingdoms fought for forty years. The salt flat was destroyed in the final battle. It is now a lake.' },
    { id:'narmir_9',  title:'The Academies',                msg:'Three great academies of learning exist in Narmir: the Ironveil for warfare, the Silversong for magic, and the Roothold for engineering. All three were founded by the same woman — a human scholar named Oryn — who lived to two hundred and twelve and is still the only person to have graduated from all three.' },
    { id:'narmir_10', title:'The Merchant Guilds',          msg:'No army has conquered as much territory as the Merchant Guilds. Operating across all race lines, they control the price of salt, iron, scrolls, and silence. It is said the Guild Masters meet once per season in a location no map shows.' },
    { id:'narmir_11', title:'The Wandering City',           msg:'Once per generation a city appears on no map, in no established territory, lasting only a few seasons before vanishing. Those who have seen it describe marble towers, streets paved in something warm, and markets selling things that should not exist. Scholars argue whether it is real. Those who have traded there do not argue.' },
    { id:'narmir_12', title:'The Hollow Mountains',         msg:'The mountain range at the centre of the continent is entirely hollow. Nobody built them that way — they were found hollow. Expeditions that enter the cave systems rarely return, and those that do come back speaking in languages no one recognises.' },
    { id:'narmir_13', title:'The Pale Tide',                msg:'Every fifth Winter, a supernatural fog rolls in from the eastern sea. Creatures emerge from it that are not animals, not monsters — something in between. Every race has a different name for them. None of the names are the same.' },
    { id:'narmir_14', title:'The Godless Age',              msg:'Narmir has no gods in the traditional sense. There were divine beings once — the Eldest — but they vanished during the Sundering. What clerics and shrine-keepers tap into is disputed: residual divine energy, collective belief, or something that does not have a name yet.' },
    { id:'narmir_15', title:'Mana Storms',                  msg:'When the Weave is disturbed by large magical events — great battles, catastrophic spells, the death of mages — it can produce a Mana Storm. Buildings shake. Animals flee. Spells cast during a storm have unpredictable effects. Every ruler dreads them. Some try to cause them.' },
    { id:'narmir_16', title:'The Tower Registry',           msg:'All mage towers in Narmir are technically registered with a body called the Registry, which theoretically has authority to inspect, restrict, or dismantle them. The Registry has seventeen clerks and no army. Nevertheless, it sends strongly worded letters and most rulers comply.' },
    { id:'narmir_17', title:'The Language of Blades',       msg:'There is a gesture-based language used exclusively by soldiers across all races — developed on battlefields where shouting gets you killed. It has over four hundred signs. The sign for "retreat" looks identical to the sign for "we won" and this has caused several historical disasters.' },
    { id:'narmir_18', title:'The First Maps',               msg:'The oldest surviving map of Narmir is wrong in almost every respect — mountains in the wrong places, seas where there are plains, cities that do not exist. Scholars believe it is not wrong. They believe the land has moved.' },
    { id:'narmir_19', title:'The Runaway Courts',           msg:'A legal tradition exists in three kingdoms whereby any citizen who can reach the nearest foreign territory without being caught by a royal guard is granted amnesty for one minor crime. This has led to elaborate public chases that have, on several occasions, accidentally started wars.' },
    { id:'narmir_20', title:'Blueprints of the Ancients',   msg:'Some architectural blueprints found in ruins do not match any known building technique. The structures they describe should collapse under their own weight — and yet the ruins of structures built from them still stand, perfectly intact, while everything around them has crumbled.' },
    { id:'narmir_21', title:'The Eclipse Compact',          msg:'During a total solar eclipse — which occurs in Narmir roughly every eleven years — all hostilities are traditionally suspended. This is not a law. It is not enforced. And yet in eight hundred years of recorded history, no war has ever been fought during an eclipse. No one can explain why.' },
    { id:'narmir_22', title:'The Sea That Flows Up',        msg:'On the western coast, there is a body of water that flows inland rather than out to sea. Ships have sailed it for hundreds of miles into the interior. It ends abruptly at a wall of rock. What power drives it upstream has never been determined.' },
    { id:'narmir_23', title:'The Word Forgers',             msg:'A sect of scholars believes that writing words in the correct sequence, in the correct ink, on the correct surface creates reality rather than recording it. They have been trying to write a city into existence for two hundred years. So far, they have a very good doorstep.' },
    { id:'narmir_24', title:'The Eternal Market',           msg:'In the ruins of the first city to fall in the Age of Crowns, a market still operates. No one owns it. No one polices it. Every day traders appear, goods change hands, and by nightfall it is empty again. Even during active sieges, the market operates.' },
    { id:'narmir_25', title:'The Unwritten Law',            msg:'Every legal system in Narmir, regardless of race, contains a final clause — worded differently each time but meaning the same thing: some acts are so terrible that no punishment exists for them because no lawmaker could bring themselves to imagine them clearly enough to write them down.' },
  ],

  // ── General lore ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  general: [
    { id:'general_1',  title:'A Wanderer\'s Note',          msg:'A mysterious traveller left this note behind at the local tavern: "Don\'t trust the roads west of the Hollow Mountains after dark. The shadows move independently of the light."' },
    { id:'general_2',  title:'The Tavern Keeper\'s Wisdom', msg:'"Every war ends at a table," said the old tavern keeper, pouring ale for the third general this season. "The question is whether the men sitting at it are the same ones who started the fighting."' },
    { id:'general_3',  title:'On the Nature of Gold',       msg:'Gold does not rust, does not rot, and does not lie. This is why every race trusts it. A gold coin from a destroyed kingdom is still worth a gold coin. The kingdom is gone. The gold remains. Think on that.' },
    { id:'general_4',  title:'The Soldier\'s Calculation',  msg:'Before any battle, a veteran soldier asks three questions: Can we win? Can we survive losing? Can we afford either? Two out of three yes answers means you fight. One means you negotiate. Zero means you retreat and pretend it was a strategic withdrawal.' },
    { id:'general_5',  title:'Maps and Territory',          msg:'A map is a lie agreed upon. The territory does not know it is being mapped. Rivers move. Mountains erode. Borders are drawn by the victors and redrawn by their children. The only honest map is the one you draw yourself, with your own feet.' },
    { id:'general_6',  title:'The Scribe\'s Burden',        msg:'Everything that ever mattered was written down by someone who was tired, underpaid, and working by bad light. Most of history is a function of eyestrain and poor ink quality. This does not make it less true. It makes it more human.' },
    { id:'general_7',  title:'On Siege Warfare',            msg:'A siege is not a battle. A siege is a negotiation conducted with starvation. The attacker is saying: your walls are impressive but your granary is finite. The defender is saying: perhaps, but winter affects both sides. The city that survives is the one that calculated correctly.' },
    { id:'general_8',  title:'The Merchant\'s Proverb',     msg:'"The first trade is always a loss. The second trade pays for the first. The third trade is where the money is. Anyone who doesn\'t make it to the third trade was not a merchant. They were a customer."' },
    { id:'general_9',  title:'On Alliances',                msg:'An alliance lasts exactly as long as both parties fear the alternative more than they resent each other. This is not cynicism. This is the entire foundation of diplomacy, and understanding it will keep you alive longer than any army.' },
    { id:'general_10', title:'The Weight of a Crown',       msg:'Leadership is not the ability to command. Any fool can shout orders. Leadership is the ability to make ten people who disagree with each other, each of whom thinks they know better, work toward the same goal long enough to accomplish it.' },
    { id:'general_11', title:'Weather and War',             msg:'More campaigns have been decided by rain than by tactics. Mud stops cavalry. Fog hides movement. Frost freezes bowstrings. Any commander who has not studied the seasonal weather patterns of the territory they intend to fight in has already lost.' },
    { id:'general_12', title:'The Engineer\'s Creed',       msg:'"A wall built in a week will fall in a month. A wall built in a year will stand for a century. A wall built in a century will become a mountain. We do not build for now. We build for whoever has to defend this after we are gone."' },
    { id:'general_13', title:'On Spies',                    msg:'A good spy does not look like a spy. They look like a merchant, a beggar, a scribe, a cook. The worst spies are the ones who look like spies — too quiet, too watchful, too good at not being noticed. True invisibility is being completely ordinary.' },
    { id:'general_14', title:'The Healer\'s Oath',          msg:'All healers in Narmir take a version of the same oath: to treat the wounded regardless of which side they fought on, to preserve life over victory, and to remember that the body does not know which kingdom it serves — only that it is in pain.' },
    { id:'general_15', title:'On Magic and Power',          msg:'Magic is not power. Gold is not power. An army is not power. Power is the ability to make other people act as you wish without having to use any of the above. The ruler who must resort to magic, gold, or soldiers has already started losing.' },
    { id:'general_16', title:'The Three Hungers',           msg:'Every kingdom is driven by three hungers: land (to feed the people), gold (to move the world), and safety (to sleep at night). A kingdom that satisfies all three becomes comfortable. A comfortable kingdom becomes slow. A slow kingdom becomes a target.' },
    { id:'general_17', title:'The Ranger\'s Rule',          msg:'"Never camp where you scouted. Never scout where you camped. Never take the same path twice. Never take a new path without knowing where it ends. The wilderness is not trying to kill you. It simply does not care whether you live."' },
    { id:'general_18', title:'On Researching the Enemy',    msg:'The greatest strategic advantage is not a bigger army. It is knowing something the enemy does not know you know. Study your opponents as carefully as your own kingdom. Their weaknesses are gifts. Their strengths are warnings.' },
    { id:'general_19', title:'The Builder\'s Paradox',      msg:'Every building is built to last forever and falls eventually. Every builder knows this and builds anyway. This is not foolishness — it is the clearest expression of hope that exists: the belief that what you make today will matter to someone you will never meet.' },
    { id:'general_20', title:'Night Watch',                 msg:'The soldiers who stand night watch are the most important soldiers in any army and the most overlooked. Battles are won by the fighters. Wars are won by the people who stayed awake long enough to notice the enemy moving in the dark.' },
    { id:'general_21', title:'On Taxes',                    msg:'A tax rate is a conversation. Too low, and the kingdom starves while the rich grow fat. Too high, and the people leave, revolt, or hide their wealth in holes in the ground. The correct rate is the highest number that still feels fair. No one agrees on what that number is.' },
    { id:'general_22', title:'The Mage\'s Warning',         msg:'"Do not confuse the ability to cast a spell with the wisdom to know when to cast it. The most powerful mage I ever knew died because he cast the right spell at the wrong moment. The spell worked perfectly. That was the problem."' },
    { id:'general_23', title:'Morale and Its Absence',      msg:'An army with low morale is not an army. It is a group of people who have not yet decided to stop fighting. The moment they make that decision, no wall, weapon, or war machine will hold them. Morale is the invisible foundation everything else rests on.' },
    { id:'general_24', title:'The Library\'s Promise',      msg:'Knowledge does not age. A scroll written five hundred years ago describing how to irrigate a field is as useful today as the day it was written. The library is not a monument to the past. It is a practical tool for the present that happens to be very old.' },
    { id:'general_25', title:'What Kingdoms Are Made Of',   msg:'A kingdom is not its walls, its army, its gold, or its ruler. It is the daily decisions of ten thousand ordinary people — to plant, to build, to trade, to stay. The moment enough of them decide to stop making those decisions, the kingdom ends. Not with a battle. With silence.' },
  ],

  // ── Dwarf lore ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  dwarf: [
    { id:'dwarf_1',  title:'The Deep Origins',              msg:'Dwarves did not descend into the mountains. They emerged from them. The oldest dwarf chronicles describe the First Clans not as miners who went underground, but as beings who remember the time before the surface existed — who watched the sky appear and found it unsettling.' },
    { id:'dwarf_2',  title:'The Stonememory',               msg:'Every dwarf carries a fragment of a geological memory passed down through bloodlines — an instinctive understanding of stone composition, fault lines, and load-bearing angles. A dwarf mason can identify the age of a wall by pressing their palm against it.' },
    { id:'dwarf_3',  title:'The Forge Gods',                msg:'Dwarves do not worship gods in the conventional sense. They revere the Seven Forge Aspects — not beings, but principles: Heat, Pressure, Patience, Precision, Strength, Purpose, and Endurance. A dwarf who embodies all seven is considered holy. None ever have.' },
    { id:'dwarf_4',  title:'The Grudge Ledgers',            msg:'Every dwarf clan maintains a Grudge Ledger — a physical book, bound in iron, listing every wrong done to the clan since its founding. When a grudge is settled, the entry is crossed out in red ink. The oldest ledgers have entries in scripts no living dwarf can read, crossed out in ink that has never dried.' },
    { id:'dwarf_5',  title:'The Hundred-Year Build',        msg:'The greatest honour in dwarf culture is not conquest or wealth. It is completing a Hundred-Year Build — a construction project begun knowing it will not be finished in one lifetime. Dwarf engineers who begin one are celebrated at death as having given the best gift: something for their children to finish.' },
    { id:'dwarf_6',  title:'Hammers and Identity',          msg:'A dwarf\'s hammer is not a tool. It is a biography. Each hammer is forged by its owner\'s parents before birth, carried throughout life, and buried with its owner. Dwarf smiths can read a life\'s story in the wear patterns of a hammer\'s head.' },
    { id:'dwarf_7',  title:'The War Machine Tradition',     msg:'Dwarf war machines are not inventions. They are arguments — physical proof that a dwarf engineer has thought of something no enemy has. Every war machine has a name, a lineage, and a technical manual written in verse. The verse is considered the more important document.' },
    { id:'dwarf_8',  title:'Gold as Language',              msg:'Dwarves do not treat gold as currency. They treat it as vocabulary. Complex transactions are conducted through precisely weighted payments where the denomination chosen communicates as much as the amount. Paying a dwarf in the wrong denomination is a social offense equivalent to shouting at a funeral.' },
    { id:'dwarf_9',  title:'The Deep Roads',                msg:'Beneath the mountain ranges run the Deep Roads — dwarf-built tunnels connecting every major stronghold. Their full extent is unknown even to dwarves. The oldest sections were dug before recorded history. Some passages have been sealed for so long that the dwarves who sealed them are now mythological figures.' },
    { id:'dwarf_10', title:'Stone Singing',                 msg:'An obscure dwarf art form involves singing at a specific resonant frequency to cause stone to shift, crack, or — in the hands of masters — to flow like slow water. The technique requires twenty years of training and ruins the singer\'s voice for normal conversation. Practitioners are deeply respected and impossible to have a quiet dinner with.' },
    { id:'dwarf_11', title:'The Iron Oath',                 msg:'The most binding promise in dwarf culture is the Iron Oath — spoken once, never repeated, never written down, and honoured until death or the explicit release of the person you made it to. A dwarf who breaks an Iron Oath loses the right to be buried with their hammer. This has happened four times in recorded history. All four are still spoken of with horror.' },
    { id:'dwarf_12', title:'Dwarf Cuisine',                 msg:'Dwarf cooking is technically impressive and culinarily bewildering. Underground agriculture produces mushrooms, fungi, cave fish, and root vegetables of extraordinary flavour, prepared using heat sources that would melt the cookware of every other race. Dwarf bread is famously used as a substitute building material in emergencies.' },
    { id:'dwarf_13', title:'The Ancestor Halls',            msg:'Every dwarf stronghold contains an Ancestor Hall — a chamber where the faces of every deceased clan member are carved into the walls. As strongholds grow older, the walls have run out of space and now extend into floors, ceilings, and dedicated tunnels. The largest known Ancestor Hall is four miles long.' },
    { id:'dwarf_14', title:'Dwarf Mathematics',             msg:'Dwarves developed a base-twelve number system independently of every other race, on the logic that twelve is more evenly divisible than ten. This makes dwarf engineering calculations extraordinarily precise and completely incomprehensible to anyone educated in the standard base-ten system.' },
    { id:'dwarf_15', title:'The Scaffold Masters',          msg:'The most elite class of dwarf engineer is not the weapons-maker or the fortress builder — it is the Scaffold Master, who specialises in making construction possible in physically impossible locations. Several of their techniques violate what other races understand about gravity.' },
    { id:'dwarf_16', title:'Trade Caravans',                msg:'Dwarf trade caravans travel overground only when necessary and only in the most heavily fortified wagons ever built. They are slow, armoured, and arrive exactly when they said they would arrive — to the minute. The penalty for tardiness in dwarf trade contracts is written in small print and enforced with enormous seriousness.' },
    { id:'dwarf_17', title:'The Gem Tongue',                msg:'Dwarf gemcutters communicate through a secret language of facet cuts visible only to trained eyes. A gem\'s value in dwarf markets is determined partly by its cut, partly by its quality, and partly by what it says — messages that have been passed under the noses of every customs official in Narmir for three hundred years.' },
    { id:'dwarf_18', title:'Dwarf Architecture',            msg:'All dwarf buildings are designed to function as fortifications at a moment\'s notice — every door reinforceable, every window a potential arrow slit, every open space designed to funnel attackers into killzones. A dwarf home has a guest room with a murder hole above the bed. This is considered hospitable.' },
    { id:'dwarf_19', title:'The Durability Philosophy',     msg:'"If it can break, build it so that breaking it costs more than it\'s worth." This principle governs every aspect of dwarf construction, from belt buckles to city gates. The corollary is: "If it must eventually break, make sure you\'re not inside it when it does." Both are taught to children before they can walk.' },
    { id:'dwarf_20', title:'Dwarf Medicine',                msg:'Dwarf medicine is primarily structural — broken bones are set with engineering precision, wounds are closed with mechanical fasteners, and recovery is managed with the same project planning used for construction. Dwarf surgeons speak of the body as a load-bearing structure that has experienced a failure event.' },
    { id:'dwarf_21', title:'The Naming Stones',             msg:'A dwarf is given three names: a birth name (private, known only to family), a work name (used in all professional contexts), and an eventual stone name (carved at death, summarising a life in seven words or fewer). The challenge of the stone name — saying everything in seven words — is considered the final creative act of a dwarf life.' },
    { id:'dwarf_22', title:'Dwarf Diplomacy',               msg:'Dwarves do not negotiate. They calculate. A dwarf diplomat arrives with precise figures: what they have, what they need, what the fair exchange value is, and what the cost of not reaching agreement will be to both parties. Meetings are short. Agreements are long. Both sides leave knowing exactly what they agreed to.' },
    { id:'dwarf_23', title:'Echoes of the Deep',            msg:'In the deepest tunnels, where no light has ever reached, dwarf children report hearing sounds that engineers have never been able to source — a regular, rhythmic tapping from somewhere below the lowest shafts. The official explanation is geological settlement. The unofficial explanation is that the dwarves who went deepest never stopped digging.' },
    { id:'dwarf_24', title:'The Patience of Stone',         msg:'"We are not slow," a dwarf elder once told a human diplomat who had been waiting three days for a response. "We are accurate. If you wanted a fast answer, you should have asked a fast question. You asked about the future. The future requires thought."' },
    { id:'dwarf_25', title:'What Dwarves Fear',             msg:'Dwarves are not afraid of the dark, depth, heat, or enemies. What they fear — the one thing that keeps dwarf engineers awake — is the flaw in the foundation. The hairline crack. The oversight in the calculation. The thing that seemed solid and wasn\'t. Most dwarf nightmares involve a wall that should not have moved.' },
  ],

  // ── High Elf lore ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  high_elf: [
    { id:'high_elf_1',  title:'The Memory Inheritance',      msg:'High Elves do not simply live long lives. They accumulate them. Each High Elf carries the emotional residue of their ancestors\' experiences — not as memories exactly, but as instincts, preferences, and occasional moments of recognition when encountering something their great-grandparents once loved.' },
    { id:'high_elf_2',  title:'The Silversong Tradition',    msg:'High Elf children are taught to sing before they are taught to speak. The Silversong — a complex harmonic tradition dating back beyond recorded history — is believed to be the original language of the Weave itself. Even partially performed, it causes subtle magical effects in the surrounding environment.' },
    { id:'high_elf_3',  title:'The Long Patience',           msg:'A High Elf diplomatic strategy that has played out over several centuries is still considered "in progress" by its architects. They have descendants. They wrote it down. From their perspective, waiting three generations for a political opening is not patience. It is planning.' },
    { id:'high_elf_4',  title:'Scroll Architecture',         msg:'High Elf libraries are not storage facilities. They are arguments made physical — scrolls and volumes arranged so that reading them in sequence leads the reader toward specific conclusions. The greatest High Elf scholars do not write books. They design reading paths through other books.' },
    { id:'high_elf_5',  title:'The Mana Courts',             msg:'High Elf governance is conducted through Mana Courts — judicial bodies where disputes are resolved by determining which party\'s argument is most harmonically aligned with the Weave. Non-elven observers describe the proceedings as "beautiful, incomprehensible, and extremely slow."' },
    { id:'high_elf_6',  title:'Elven Starcraft',             msg:'High Elves navigate by stars with a precision that goes beyond astronomy. They maintain charts recording every star\'s position over thousands of years, allowing them to calculate not just where a traveller is but when they are — identifying the season and year from a single clear night sky.' },
    { id:'high_elf_7',  title:'The Quiet War',               msg:'High Elves and Dark Elves have been at war for nine hundred years. Neither side discusses it. Both sides deny it. The conflict is conducted entirely through economic manipulation, strategic marriage alliances, subtle magical interference, and the occasional assassination that both sides call "an unfortunate accident."' },
    { id:'high_elf_8',  title:'Mage Tower Philosophy',       msg:'A High Elf mage tower is not a military installation. It is a research instrument. Every architectural decision — window placement, chamber dimensions, spiral angle of the stairs — is designed to maximise Weave interaction. The most powerful towers took two hundred years to build and look nothing like towers to non-elven eyes.' },
    { id:'high_elf_9',  title:'The Price of Long Life',      msg:'High Elves experience time differently from mortal races — not slowly, but with a different weight. Human friendships last decades and feel like lifetimes. High Elf friendships last centuries and still end. Every High Elf who lives long enough collects a private archive of everyone they have outlived. It is the heaviest thing they carry.' },
    { id:'high_elf_10', title:'The Woven Script',            msg:'Written High Elven is not a representation of spoken language. It is a representation of magical structure — each character a Weave configuration, each sentence a spell that describes rather than creates. High Elven documents can be read as literature or cast as ritual. Occasionally, both at once.' },
    { id:'high_elf_11', title:'Scroll Craft',                msg:'A High Elf-crafted scroll is not ink on parchment. It is a compressed magical event waiting to be released. The parchment is prepared over months. The ink is alchemical. The writing process is itself a form of casting. A scroll made carelessly is not less powerful — it is unpredictable, which is worse.' },
    { id:'high_elf_12', title:'The Grove Courts',            msg:'High Elf settlements are grown rather than built. Trees are trained over generations into structural shapes; plants are alchemically treated to have the load-bearing properties of stone. The oldest High Elf cities are indistinguishable from old-growth forest to the untrained eye. This is intentional.' },
    { id:'high_elf_13', title:'Elven Music and Memory',      msg:'High Elf music is not entertainment. It is recordkeeping. Complex historical events are encoded in musical compositions — every melody a fact, every harmony a relationship, every rest a silence that speaks. The full history of the Sundering exists as a four-hour orchestral piece that licensed historians must learn to perform in order to quote it accurately.' },
    { id:'high_elf_14', title:'The Spellbinders',            msg:'The most powerful High Elf mages do not cast spells. They bind them — creating standing magical effects that persist indefinitely, maintained by Weave resonance rather than active concentration. The oldest known bound spell has been running for four hundred years. No one knows what it does. No one dares to dispel it.' },
    { id:'high_elf_15', title:'Trade Through Proxies',       msg:'High Elves rarely trade directly. They maintain networks of agents — non-elven merchants who buy, sell, and negotiate on their behalf at three levels of remove. This is not arrogance. It is strategic ambiguity: if no one knows what High Elves want, no one can accurately calculate what they\'re willing to pay.' },
    { id:'high_elf_16', title:'The Art of Forgetting',       msg:'With such long memories, High Elves have developed the Art of Forgetting — a mental discipline allowing deliberate release of accumulated emotional weight. It is considered the most difficult skill to master and the most necessary. Elves who cannot forget eventually stop engaging with the present entirely.' },
    { id:'high_elf_17', title:'The Second Tongue',           msg:'All High Elves are fluent in at least one non-elven language before they are considered adults. The reasoning is diplomatic: "You cannot understand what someone wants if you cannot think in their language." The most educated High Elves are fluent in all six major racial languages and several extinct ones.' },
    { id:'high_elf_18', title:'Elven Perception of Magic',   msg:'Non-elven mages describe magic as a force they use. High Elves describe it as a presence they coexist with. The distinction, which sounds philosophical, has profound practical implications: High Elf spells are less powerful individually but more harmonically stable — they do not fight the Weave, they converse with it.' },
    { id:'high_elf_19', title:'The Thousand-Year Grudge',    msg:'High Elves do not maintain Grudge Ledgers like dwarves. Instead, they maintain the Long Consideration — a mental catalogue of unresolved debts, both owed and owing, which informs every interaction without being spoken. A High Elf who brings up a Long Consideration in conversation is issuing a formal warning.' },
    { id:'high_elf_20', title:'Diplomatic Architecture',     msg:'The design of meeting spaces matters deeply to High Elves. They will refuse to negotiate in a room with poor acoustics, bad light, or furniture arranged to give either party a positional advantage. The preparation of a meeting room is considered as important as the negotiation itself.' },
    { id:'high_elf_21', title:'The Bloodline Schools',       msg:'High Elf magical ability is not entirely innate — it is cultivated through Bloodline Schools, intensive multi-generational training programs that shape magical development across family lines. A student enters a Bloodline School knowing that their children will inherit the benefits of their training. This is the most extreme form of delayed gratification known to exist.' },
    { id:'high_elf_22', title:'On Human Allies',             msg:'High Elves find humans baffling and fascinating in equal measure — creatures of extraordinary urgency who accomplish in a single lifetime what elves spend centuries planning. The most common High Elf reaction to humans is not contempt but something closer to awe mixed with anxiety: what could they accomplish if they slowed down?' },
    { id:'high_elf_23', title:'The Elven Silence',           msg:'High Elves use silence communicatively in ways that no other race has decoded. The length, texture, and context of an elven pause carries as much meaning as the words around it. Non-elven diplomats are advised never to fill an elven silence — what you say into it becomes part of the conversation in ways you may not intend.' },
    { id:'high_elf_24', title:'Magic Without Words',         msg:'The highest achievement in High Elf magic is wordless casting — producing magical effects through pure Weave harmonics without incantation, gesture, or material components. It is indistinguishable from doing nothing. The most powerful High Elf mages in history are rumoured to have resolved wars by sitting quietly in adjacent rooms.' },
    { id:'high_elf_25', title:'The Weight of Memory',        msg:'"We remember everything," an elderly elf once told a human historian. "Which means we forget nothing — not the good things, not the terrible things. Not the friends who died before us, not the mistakes we made three centuries ago. You ask why elves seem sad. It is not sadness. It is the weight of a very full library."' },
  ],

  // ── Orc lore ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  orc: [
    { id:'orc_1',  title:'The First Warbands',              msg:'Orcs did not build the first civilisations. They dismantled them — and from the wreckage, built something harder, faster, and more honest. The first orc settlements were made entirely from the materials of defeated enemies. This was not vandalism. It was recycling, orc-style.' },
    { id:'orc_2',  title:'The Strength Doctrine',           msg:'Orcish culture is not about the worship of strength. It is about the pursuit of it — the belief that every individual and every community is capable of becoming more than they currently are, and that the only honest way to measure progress is direct competition. "Stronger than yesterday" is the closest thing orcs have to a prayer.' },
    { id:'orc_3',  title:'The War Name',                    msg:'An orc is born with a clan name. They earn a war name. The war name is not given — it is taken, from the first moment of exceptional action that others witness. Some orcs carry their war names proudly for centuries. Some die with only a clan name. Both outcomes are respected, but only one is celebrated.' },
    { id:'orc_4',  title:'Orcish Economics',                msg:'Orcish trade runs on a reputation economy before it runs on gold. An orc merchant who has never defaulted on a deal is more creditworthy than any written contract. The handshake is not a formality — it is the binding document, witnessed by everyone present, to be enforced by everyone present if violated.' },
    { id:'orc_5',  title:'The Great Hunts',                 msg:'Twice per year, orc clans organise the Great Hunt — not for food (markets handle that) but for the maintenance of collective skill, social bonding, and the particular joy of doing something difficult together. The Great Hunt has accidentally solved several food shortages and started three minor wars.' },
    { id:'orc_6',  title:'Battlefield Medicine',            msg:'Orcs developed the most efficient battlefield medicine in Narmir — not because they value life above other races, but because keeping warriors functional is a tactical advantage. An orc field medic can diagnose, treat, and return a soldier to action faster than any other race\'s equivalent. The techniques are brutal, effective, and not recommended for the faint-hearted.' },
    { id:'orc_7',  title:'The Grudge Fight',                msg:'When two orcs have a serious dispute, they resolve it through the Grudge Fight — a structured combat with agreed rules, witnessed by clan elders, which ends when one party yields or cannot continue. The loser owes the winner a single favour, the scale of which is determined by how the fight ended. This has largely replaced both lawsuits and vendettas.' },
    { id:'orc_8',  title:'Orcish Architecture',             msg:'Orc buildings are designed to be built in days and to withstand siege for months. Every component is standardised, interchangeable, and repairable with field tools. An orc fortress looks improvised. From a structural engineering standpoint, it is not. Every joint is exactly where the load calculations say it should be.' },
    { id:'orc_9',  title:'The Clan Assembly',               msg:'Major orc decisions are made by the Clan Assembly — every adult member of the clan, voting by show of hands, with the loudest voice not the deciding factor. The deciding factor is majority. An orc leader who cannot carry the Assembly cannot lead. This system has produced spectacularly bad decisions made with great collective conviction, and occasionally the reverse.' },
    { id:'orc_10', title:'War Machines and Pride',          msg:'Orc war machines are not precision instruments. They are statements. A dwarf war machine is built to exact tolerances. An orc war machine is built to make the enemy reconsider their choices. The two philosophies produce very different machines, both of which are highly effective at destroying the things they are pointed at.' },
    { id:'orc_11', title:'Orcish Cuisine',                  msg:'Orc cooking is high-volume, high-calorie, and unapologetically carnivorous. An orc campaign kitchen can feed five thousand soldiers in under an hour using equipment that fits in three wagons. The result tastes like motivation and smells like victory. Non-orcs eat it once, usually under duress, and are surprised to find they want seconds.' },
    { id:'orc_12', title:'The Silence Before Battle',       msg:'In the hour before a major engagement, orc warbands go completely silent. No drums, no war cries, no preparation noise. It is not fear. It is the particular quality of attention that orcs bring to the things they take seriously. An enemy who has seen this silence and underestimated it rarely gets the opportunity to make that mistake twice.' },
    { id:'orc_13', title:'Trade Routes and Raiding',        msg:'The distinction between an orc trade caravan and an orc raiding party is often simply paperwork. Both carry goods. Both have armed escorts. The difference is whether the other party agreed in advance to give up their valuables. Orc merchants consider this distinction important. Other races consider it a technicality.' },
    { id:'orc_14', title:'The Clan Mother',                 msg:'Behind every famous orc warlord is a Clan Mother — the senior female elder who controls clan resources, resolves internal disputes, and provides the strategic perspective that balances the tactical focus of the war leaders. Clan Mothers are rarely seen in histories written by other races. This is why those histories keep getting the outcome of orc conflicts wrong.' },
    { id:'orc_15', title:'Orcish Honesty',                  msg:'Orcs are legendarily direct — not because they lack subtlety, but because indirect communication wastes time that could be spent on more interesting things. An orc insult is a gift: it tells you exactly what the orc thinks of you. An orc compliment is given once, never repeated, and remembered forever by the person who received it.' },
    { id:'orc_16', title:'The Stronghold Tradition',        msg:'An orc clan does not consider itself established until it has built and defended a stronghold for at least one full seasonal cycle. A clan without a defended stronghold is a warband. A clan that has held one for ten years is a people. The distinction matters to orcs in ways that outsiders frequently underestimate.' },
    { id:'orc_17', title:'Orcish Research',                 msg:'Orc research is almost entirely applied. The question "why does this work?" is considered less interesting than "what can we do with the fact that it works?" This produces technology that is occasionally baffling in origin and consistently reliable in practice. Orcish catapult range tables were compiled entirely empirically and are more accurate than any theoretically derived equivalent.' },
    { id:'orc_18', title:'The Songs of the Fallen',         msg:'Every orc who dies in combat is commemorated in a song that begins "Here is what they did." Not "here is who they were" or "here is what they believed." What they did. The deeds are catalogued, the song is sung once at the funeral, and then it is the responsibility of the clan to remember it without writing it down.' },
    { id:'orc_19', title:'Orc Diplomacy',                   msg:'Orc diplomats negotiate as if the conversation is a fight — not a fight to win, but a fight to determine who the stronger party is, with mutual respect the outcome of that determination. An orc who concedes a point does so loudly, deliberately, and in a way that makes clear they are choosing to concede, not being forced to. The distinction is everything.' },
    { id:'orc_20', title:'Children of the Warband',         msg:'Orc children are raised collectively by the warband, not just by parents. Every adult takes responsibility for every child. This produces adults who are deeply loyal to their clan and genuinely bewildered by the concept of a family that does not include everyone they grew up near.' },
    { id:'orc_21', title:'The Challenge of Excellence',     msg:'The highest cultural value in orcish society is not victory. It is excellence under pressure — the ability to perform at one\'s best when the stakes are highest. A warrior who wins through luck is tolerated. A warrior who performs beautifully and loses is celebrated. A warrior who performs beautifully and wins is legendary.' },
    { id:'orc_22', title:'Orcish Governance',               msg:'Orc governance is not simple — it is direct. Laws are few, clearly stated, and enforced consistently. The legal code of the largest orc federation fits on four sides of a single page. This produces a society where almost everything is legal and the few things that are illegal are treated with absolute seriousness.' },
    { id:'orc_23', title:'On Other Races',                  msg:'"Dwarves take forever to do anything and the result lasts forever. Elves take forever to decide and the decision is usually right. Humans do everything immediately and are always surprised by the consequences. We prefer to do things correctly, quickly, and loudly. Everyone finds this unsettling. We consider this a feature."' },
    { id:'orc_24', title:'The River Crossings',             msg:'The most celebrated moment in orcish military history is not a victory. It is the crossing of the Ashrock River under heavy fire during the Third Compact War — a logistical nightmare executed with precise timing and no survivors from the forward units. "They knew," goes the memorial. "They crossed anyway."' },
    { id:'orc_25', title:'What Orcs Build Toward',          msg:'Ask an orc what they are building and they will say: a future where their grandchildren do not have to apologise for existing. Every fortress wall, every trade route, every warband is ultimately in service of this. They have been called warlike. They prefer the term: thorough.' },
  ],

  // ── Dark Elf lore ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  dark_elf: [
    { id:'dark_elf_1',  title:'The Schism',                 msg:'Dark Elves did not always exist as a separate people. They emerged from a philosophical disagreement within the ancient elf civilisation — a faction who believed that magic should be used to reshape the world, not merely coexist with it. The separation was not violent at first. Then it was.' },
    { id:'dark_elf_2',  title:'The Shadow Courts',          msg:'Dark Elf governance operates through Shadow Courts — bodies that officially do not exist, making decisions that officially never happened, about matters that are officially denied. This is not corruption. It is a sophisticated system of plausible deniability so thoroughly institutionalised that it has its own etiquette, its own legal theory, and its own history books (which are classified).' },
    { id:'dark_elf_3',  title:'The Art of the Mask',        msg:'Dark Elves maintain multiple identities as a cultural practice — not deception but precision. The self shown to allies differs from the self shown to enemies, which differs from the self shown in private. The true self is the one that decides which mask to wear. Only a fool or a friend sees all of them.' },
    { id:'dark_elf_4',  title:'Covert Magic',               msg:'Dark Elf magic specialises in concealment, misdirection, and the manipulation of perception. Their most advanced practitioners can make objects invisible, make themselves undetectable to magical senses, and — in legend, though no one has confirmed this — make events appear to have happened differently than they did.' },
    { id:'dark_elf_5',  title:'The Spider\'s Web',          msg:'Dark Elf intelligence networks are described by rivals as a spider\'s web — not because spiders are sinister, but because the web is invisible until you are in it, and by then you are already caught. The metaphor is one that Dark Elves accept and, privately, have made their informal emblem.' },
    { id:'dark_elf_6',  title:'Market Shadows',             msg:'Dark Elf black markets operate in every major city in Narmir regardless of laws, city guards, or diplomatic protests. They operate in shadow not because what is sold is always illegal, but because the Dark Elves found long ago that things sold in shadow fetch higher prices. Mystery has a market value.' },
    { id:'dark_elf_7',  title:'The Price of Knowledge',     msg:'"We do not sell information. We sell introductions to information." The distinction, which Dark Elf information brokers consider critical, means their clients cannot accuse them of providing false data — only of arranging a meeting where false data was encountered. This has held up in every court it has been tested in.' },
    { id:'dark_elf_8',  title:'Ninja Culture',              msg:'The Dark Elf ninja tradition is not an assassin\'s guild. It is a philosophy of invisibility — the belief that the most powerful position is one that cannot be threatened because it cannot be located. A Dark Elf ninja\'s highest achievement is completing an objective that no one ever realises required a ninja.' },
    { id:'dark_elf_9',  title:'The Long Investment',        msg:'Dark Elves play strategies that span generations. An agent placed in a rival court as a child may not deliver actionable intelligence for forty years. The patience required is not cold-bloodedness — it is an alternative relationship with time, in which fifty years is a reasonable investment horizon.' },
    { id:'dark_elf_10', title:'Alchemy and Shadow',         msg:'Dark Elf alchemy focuses on substances that affect perception, memory, and awareness — not poisons in the crude sense, but precision pharmacological tools. Many are legal. Several are widely sold. Their most valuable products are the ones that make the recipient unable to remember acquiring them.' },
    { id:'dark_elf_11', title:'The Loyalty Calculation',    msg:'Dark Elves do not give loyalty freely. They give it calculatingly — and it is absolute once given, calibrated precisely to the value of the relationship. Betraying a Dark Elf ally is considered one of the most strategically foolish acts possible, not for moral reasons but practical ones: they never forget, they plan in decades, and they are very good at their particular specialities.' },
    { id:'dark_elf_12', title:'Fashion as Intelligence',    msg:'Dark Elf clothing carries information. Every design choice — fabric, cut, colour, embellishment — communicates social status, political affiliation, and current loyalties to anyone who knows the code. At formal Dark Elf gatherings, the most important conversations take place without words, through the deliberate arrangement of accessories.' },
    { id:'dark_elf_13', title:'The Listening City',         msg:'The Dark Elf capital is called the Listening City. It has no other name. Every public space has been architecturally designed to carry whispers from one end to another, so that the city\'s administrators hear everything spoken in them. Citizens have learned to whisper elsewhere. The city listens to that, too.' },
    { id:'dark_elf_14', title:'Night Markets',              msg:'Dark Elf settlements reverse the standard schedule — markets, courts, and social events occur at night; sleep happens during the day. Visitors who spend time in Dark Elf territory report a disorienting sense that the world is more active at 3am than at noon. They are correct. They are also, almost certainly, being observed.' },
    { id:'dark_elf_15', title:'The Thieves\' Academy',      msg:'The Thieves\' Academy does not teach theft. It teaches access — the ability to be in any place without permission, acquire any object without detection, and leave any situation without consequence. Graduates pursue careers in intelligence work, exploration, diplomacy, and, occasionally, theft.' },
    { id:'dark_elf_16', title:'Written and Unwritten Law',  msg:'Dark Elf society operates under two parallel legal systems: the written law (public, fair, and followed with scrupulous precision) and the unwritten law (private, flexible, and governing everything the written law does not cover, which is everything that matters). Both are enforced. Only one is admitted to exist.' },
    { id:'dark_elf_17', title:'The Exchange Rate of Secrets', msg:'"A secret known to one person has no value. A secret known to two people has enormous value. A secret known to three people is no longer a secret — it is a rumour with pretensions." This principle governs all Dark Elf information economics and explains why they are very careful about who counts as two.' },
    { id:'dark_elf_18', title:'Dark Elf Architecture',      msg:'Dark Elf buildings are beautiful, confusing, and deliberately non-Euclidean in layout. Visitors regularly get lost. This is not a design flaw. Every dead end has a window. Every confusing corridor has a guard post. The architecture is the security system.' },
    { id:'dark_elf_19', title:'On High Elves',              msg:'The Dark Elf position on High Elves is nuanced, deeply personal, and centuries old. It is not hatred — it is complicated. The most accurate description, offered by a Dark Elf philosopher, was: "We are what they chose not to become. They are what we decided to leave behind. Neither of us is entirely comfortable with what that means."' },
    { id:'dark_elf_20', title:'The Inheritance of Grudges', msg:'Dark Elves pass down both wealth and grievances through family lines — the latter more reliably than the former. A Dark Elf child may inherit a political conflict three generations old alongside their parent\'s furniture. The conflict comes with documentation, context, and a recommended strategy. The furniture is also nice.' },
    { id:'dark_elf_21', title:'Assassination as Argument',  msg:'Dark Elves do not view assassination as violence. They view it as a form of persuasion — the ultimate statement that an individual\'s continued existence is incompatible with a desired outcome. They find the moral outrage of other races baffling, given that large-scale warfare is considered acceptable while targeted intervention is not.' },
    { id:'dark_elf_22', title:'The Patron System',          msg:'Every Dark Elf of consequence has a patron and is a patron to others — a network of obligation, favour, and mutual advantage that constitutes both a social safety net and an intelligence apparatus. To have no patron is to be invisible in the worst sense: not dangerous and useful, just irrelevant.' },
    { id:'dark_elf_23', title:'Silence as Power',           msg:'The most feared sentence in Dark Elf culture is not a threat. It is an absence — when a powerful individual stops acknowledging you in social contexts. Not an insult, not an attack. Simply: you no longer exist to them. This is considered more serious than most physical consequences.' },
    { id:'dark_elf_24', title:'The True Face',              msg:'In a culture of masks and calculated presentations, the highest compliment a Dark Elf can pay is to drop all performance in your presence — to be, briefly, not anyone they need to be for any reason. It is rare. It is unmistakable. And it means, more clearly than any words could say, that you are trusted.' },
    { id:'dark_elf_25', title:'What Dark Elves Want',       msg:'Other races spend considerable effort trying to determine what Dark Elves actually want, underneath the politics and the shadows and the information brokering. The answer, according to the only Dark Elf elder who ever answered the question directly, is: "The same thing everyone wants. To be safe. To be free. To be, occasionally, underestimated."' },
  ],

  // ── Human lore ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  human: [
    { id:'human_1',  title:'The Adaptable Race',            msg:'Humans have no exceptional gifts. They are not as strong as orcs, as precise as dwarves, as magical as elves, or as perceptive as dire wolves. What they have is the ability to become any of those things, to a lesser degree, very quickly. Every other race has noticed this and found it either inspiring or terrifying.' },
    { id:'human_2',  title:'The Short Memory Problem',       msg:'Human civilisations make the same mistakes every three generations because three generations is long enough for the consequences to fade and short enough for the pattern to recur. Every other race has a word for this phenomenon. Dwarves call it "the human cycle." High Elves call it "tragic." Orcs call it "predictable." Humans call it "history."' },
    { id:'human_3',  title:'The City Builders',             msg:'Humans build cities the way other races breathe — constantly, compulsively, and without always thinking through the implications. No other race has produced as many cities that should not exist in the locations where they were built, and yet somehow continue to function through sheer collective will and good drainage.' },
    { id:'human_4',  title:'The Diplomatic Tradition',      msg:'Humans are the only race to have allied, at one point or another, with every other race in Narmir. This is not because they are trusted — it is because they are useful, relatively predictable in their short-term behaviour, and willing to sign almost anything with enough encouragement.' },
    { id:'human_5',  title:'The Innovation Gap',            msg:'Human technology advances faster than any other race\'s — not because humans are smarter, but because they have shorter lives and therefore more generations per century, each one inheriting the previous generation\'s knowledge and immediately trying to improve it. The compounding effect is remarkable and slightly alarming.' },
    { id:'human_6',  title:'Religion and the Humans',       msg:'Humans have more religions than any other race, serving more gods, requiring more specific behaviours, and producing more internal conflict over theological minutiae. Other races regard this with a mixture of fascination and concern. Humans regard it as normal. They find the idea of a race with no religious disagreements unsettling.' },
    { id:'human_7',  title:'The Trade Networks',            msg:'Human trade networks are the most extensive in Narmir — not because of superior goods but because of superior persistence. A human merchant turned away by a potential partner does not go home. They try again, through a different route, with a different proposition, at a different price. Eventually, most of them find a deal.' },
    { id:'human_8',  title:'War and Its Aftermath',         msg:'Humans are the only race to have developed a substantial body of post-war reconciliation practice — not because they are more peaceful, but because they fight more frequently and have therefore had more practice at stopping. Human peace treaties are the most comprehensive in Narmir and typically last until the generation that signed them dies.' },
    { id:'human_9',  title:'The Royal Succession Problem',  msg:'More human kingdoms have ended through succession disputes than through conquest. The combination of a short lifespan, unclear inheritance laws, and the human tendency to have many children by many partners has produced an extraordinary body of legal precedent, most of it written in blood.' },
    { id:'human_10', title:'Human Architecture',            msg:'Human buildings are built quickly, repaired constantly, modified continuously, and occasionally collapse. The humans inside them accept this as a reasonable trade-off for having a building in less than a generation. Most human cities are palimpsests — layers of construction and reconstruction through which the oldest foundations can still be found, somewhere, if you dig.' },
    { id:'human_11', title:'The Soldier\'s Culture',        msg:'Human military culture varies enormously across kingdoms but shares a universal core: the idea that ordinary people, trained and motivated, can do extraordinary things. This has been proved true often enough to constitute a strategic doctrine, and false often enough to fill several memorial halls.' },
    { id:'human_12', title:'Human Magic',                   msg:'Human mages are neither the most powerful nor the most precise in Narmir. What they are is experimental. Every other race has established magical traditions passed down through lineages. Humans have schools, academies, competing theories, and a notable willingness to try things that the traditions say shouldn\'t work. Some of these attempts end badly. Some produce new spells no other race thought of.' },
    { id:'human_13', title:'The Farming Heritage',          msg:'Humans are the most successful farmers in Narmir — not because of magical gifts, but because of relentless agricultural innovation over centuries. Human grain varieties, irrigation systems, and soil management practices have been adopted by every other race. The greatest contribution humans have made to Narmir is, arguably, bread.' },
    { id:'human_14', title:'The Problem of Heroes',         msg:'Human cultures produce heroes at a higher rate than any other race and have more difficulty knowing what to do with them afterwards. The hero who saves the kingdom becomes the general who wins the war becomes the politician who governs the peace becomes the problem that the next hero has to solve. This cycle has been noted. It continues.' },
    { id:'human_15', title:'On Other Races',                msg:'"We have been conquered by orcs, taught by elves, built for by dwarves, robbed by dark elves, and guided through wilderness by dire wolves. We have outlasted every empire that conquered us, graduated every school that taught us, and still live in the buildings dwarves built. We are the students who will not stop enrolling."' },
    { id:'human_16', title:'The Cleric Tradition',          msg:'Human clerics are not the most powerful healers in Narmir but they are the most common. Their training is accessible, their methods are teachable without magical talent, and their presence on battlefields has been calculated to reduce casualties by approximately a third. Every human army includes them. Every enemy army wishes it did.' },
    { id:'human_17', title:'Human Resilience',              msg:'No other race has recovered from civilisational collapse as frequently as humans. Three times in recorded history, human kingdoms have been reduced to isolated villages by conquest, plague, or catastrophe. Three times, they have rebuilt to regional power within two generations. Other races find this either inspiring or deeply inconvenient.' },
    { id:'human_18', title:'The Merchant Princes',          msg:'The wealthiest humans in Narmir are not kings. They are merchants who have accumulated enough gold to make kings largely ceremonial. The Merchant Princes — a semi-formal class of commercial aristocracy — govern through financial leverage rather than military force, which is slower to mobilise but considerably more durable.' },
    { id:'human_19', title:'The Common Tongue',             msg:'The trade language of Narmir is human in origin — simplified, pragmatic, and stripped of the grammatical precision that makes other racial languages difficult to learn quickly. It was not designed as a lingua franca. It became one because humans traded so widely that knowing human was the most profitable linguistic investment.' },
    { id:'human_20', title:'Human Curiosity',               msg:'The defining human characteristic — more than their adaptability, their breeding rate, or their political instability — is curiosity. Humans enter places they were warned not to enter, ask questions they were told not to ask, and attempt things that experience clearly indicates are inadvisable. The results are, statistically, mixed. The aggregate outcome has been extraordinary.' },
    { id:'human_21', title:'The Kingdom Cycle',             msg:'Students of political history have identified a recurring pattern in human kingdoms: founding, expansion, consolidation, corruption, reform, and either collapse or renewed founding. The cycle averages about two hundred years. It has been identified, described, taught in schools, and continues to occur on schedule regardless.' },
    { id:'human_22', title:'Human Festivals',               msg:'Humans celebrate everything. Births, deaths, harvests, plantings, military victories, military defeats (with a different tone), seasonal changes, founding anniversaries, the birthdays of deceased leaders, and a number of events whose original significance has been entirely forgotten but whose associated food is too good to abandon.' },
    { id:'human_23', title:'The Refugee Tradition',         msg:'Human kingdoms absorb refugees from other races more readily than any other society — not from altruism but from practicality: more people means more workers, more soldiers, more taxpayers, and more innovation. The diversity of human cities is sometimes presented as a virtue. It is also a trade policy.' },
    { id:'human_24', title:'Human Stubbornness',            msg:'It has been calculated that removing humans from a contested territory requires, on average, three times more effort than removing any other race. They do not surrender locations they have decided to hold, regardless of strategic logic, supply situation, or the opinions of the senior command. This is a significant tactical problem for their enemies and an occasional tactical problem for their own generals.' },
    { id:'human_25', title:'What It Means To Be Human',     msg:'"We are not the strongest. We are not the most ancient. We do not have the longest memories or the deepest magic or the sharpest senses. What we have is a refusal to believe that any of that matters as much as what you do with what you have. We are the race that decided limitations are the interesting part."' },
  ],

  // ── Dire Wolf lore ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  dire_wolf: [
    { id:'dire_wolf_1',  title:'The Pack Origin',           msg:'Dire Wolves are the youngest intelligent race in Narmir — their emergence from pure animal consciousness to self-aware civilisation occurred within the last eight hundred years, a blink in historical terms. Other races were already building empires when dire wolves had their first political argument. They have been catching up with extraordinary speed and considerable ferocity.' },
    { id:'dire_wolf_2',  title:'The Pack Bond',             msg:'The Pack Bond is not a metaphor. It is a low-level magical connection between pack members — a shared awareness of emotional state, physical wellbeing, and approximate location. A dire wolf always knows if a packmate is injured. A pack that loses a member feels the absence as a physical sensation for weeks. This is why dire wolves fight so hard to bring their people home.' },
    { id:'dire_wolf_3',  title:'The Alpha System',          msg:'Dire wolf leadership is not inherited or elected. It is continuously re-established through a combination of demonstrated competence, physical capability, and the consent of the pack. An Alpha who loses the pack\'s confidence does not lose their title at a scheduled election. They lose it the next morning, when no one follows them.' },
    { id:'dire_wolf_4',  title:'Hunter\'s Sight',           msg:'Dire wolf perception operates on frequencies unavailable to other races. They see motion at distances that other races cannot resolve, hear at ranges that allow them to track prey from miles away, and smell emotional states with a precision that makes diplomacy in their presence uncomfortable for anyone with something to hide.' },
    { id:'dire_wolf_5',  title:'The Great Hunt Tradition',  msg:'The Great Hunt is not an annual event for dire wolves. It is a constant practice — the ongoing training of the entire pack in coordinated pursuit, ambush, and the identification of weaknesses in prey. What other races call military exercises, dire wolves call Tuesday.' },
    { id:'dire_wolf_6',  title:'Territory and Its Meaning', msg:'Dire wolves do not own territory in the legal sense. They inhabit it — a distinction that has caused significant diplomatic confusion. From a dire wolf perspective, territory belongs to whoever knows it best, uses it most effectively, and can defend it. Documentation is for species that do not trust their own memory.' },
    { id:'dire_wolf_7',  title:'The First Language',        msg:'The original dire wolf language is primarily non-verbal — a complex system of posture, scent marking, vocalisation pitch, and movement that communicates with extraordinary precision. The verbal language they developed for interaction with other races is a secondary system, used willingly but considered slightly imprecise, like translating poetry.' },
    { id:'dire_wolf_8',  title:'Pack Warfare',              msg:'Dire wolf military tactics are pack-based — distributed, coordinated without centralised command, and terrifyingly effective against ordered formations. The signal to attack is not a trumpet. It is a change in collective behaviour that the pack reads instinctively, simultaneous, from multiple angles, at a speed that leaves no time to respond.' },
    { id:'dire_wolf_9',  title:'The Den Culture',           msg:'Dire wolf settlements are built below ground and above it simultaneously — den systems for sleeping, raising young, and storing resources; surface structures for defence, social interaction, and the maintenance of perimeter awareness. The above-ground structures are austere. The dens are warm, complex, and lined with things that matter.' },
    { id:'dire_wolf_10', title:'Ranger Tradition',          msg:'Dire wolf rangers are not scouts in the conventional sense. They are the pack\'s relationship with its territory — beings who know every path, every seasonal change, every predator and source of food within their range. A dire wolf ranger who is asked for directions does not give directions. They offer to take you there.' },
    { id:'dire_wolf_11', title:'The Scar Culture',          msg:'Scars in dire wolf culture are not hidden. They are displayed, explained, and valued as evidence of experience survived. Every scar has a story. Learning the story is considered a way of knowing the individual. A dire wolf who has no scars is young. A dire wolf who has many is worth listening to.' },
    { id:'dire_wolf_12', title:'Dire Wolf Trade',           msg:'Dire wolves trade in goods that other races overlook: exceptional hides, wilderness knowledge, tracking services, and the kind of geographic intelligence that only centuries of living in a territory can produce. They are not wealthy by gold standards. By information standards, they are very rich indeed.' },
    { id:'dire_wolf_13', title:'The Moon Calendar',         msg:'Dire wolves track time by the moon rather than the sun — a habit that predates their development of language. Their calendar has thirty-seven named moon phases, each with associated traditional activities, emotional connotations, and dietary recommendations. The calendar is also a medical document: different moon phases are associated with different healing practices, and the data behind this correlation is, to say the least, interesting.' },
    { id:'dire_wolf_14', title:'On Loyalty',                msg:'"We do not understand conditional loyalty," said a dire wolf elder to a human ambassador who had proposed a contingency clause in their alliance treaty. "Either you run with us or you do not. If you are in our pack, you are in our pack until you leave or until we ask you to leave. There is no clause for maybe."' },
    { id:'dire_wolf_15', title:'The First Packs',           msg:'The founding packs of dire wolf civilisation did not begin with politics or economics. They began with a question asked by an animal that had just become capable of asking it: "If I am aware, are the others like me also aware?" The answer to that question, pursued with characteristic direct intensity, became a civilisation.' },
    { id:'dire_wolf_16', title:'Expedition Culture',        msg:'Every young dire wolf is expected to undertake at least one solo expedition — a journey into unknown territory, lasting as long as it takes, for the purpose of learning what they are capable of without the pack. Many return within weeks. Some are gone for years. All of them come back changed. This is the point.' },
    { id:'dire_wolf_17', title:'The Speed Doctrine',        msg:'Dire wolf military philosophy is built on a single principle: be where the enemy does not expect you, faster than they can respond. They do not build fortifications. They build speed — physical fitness, supply efficiency, route knowledge, and the ability to cover ground that other armies would take a week to cross in a day.' },
    { id:'dire_wolf_18', title:'Dire Wolf Cuisine',         msg:'Dire wolf food culture divides opinion sharply among other races. Their preference for raw or minimally cooked protein, consumed in large quantities after periods of hard activity, is biologically sensible and culinarily challenging. Their fermented preservation techniques, however, have been adopted across Narmir under different names.' },
    { id:'dire_wolf_19', title:'Pack Memory',               msg:'Dire wolf oral history is maintained through a practice called the Running Memory — stories told while running, at pace, so that the physical rhythm becomes associated with the narrative. Pack members can recall Running Memory stories with unusual accuracy for this reason. The technique is exhausting for non-dire-wolves and has never been successfully adopted by any other race.' },
    { id:'dire_wolf_20', title:'On Other Races',            msg:'"Dwarves build things that last and are pleased about it. Elves build things that grow and are pleased about it. Humans build things that change and are surprised about it. Orcs build things that survive and are satisfied about it. We build relationships that matter and consider everything else secondary."' },
    { id:'dire_wolf_21', title:'The Fang Oath',             msg:'The Fang Oath is the most serious commitment in dire wolf culture — sworn not with words but with the physical act of touching fangs, committing both individuals to mutual defence, honest communication, and shared consequence. It is not a formality. It has never been broken in recorded history. This is considered less a testament to dire wolf virtue than to their very thorough understanding of what they are swearing.' },
    { id:'dire_wolf_22', title:'Healing Traditions',        msg:'Dire wolf medicine draws on centuries of observing how injured animals recover — which plants accelerate healing, which behaviours slow it, which injuries benefit from activity and which require rest. Their wound treatment protocols are derived entirely from empirical observation and are, in several specific applications, more effective than the theoretically developed medicine of other races.' },
    { id:'dire_wolf_23', title:'The Question of Cities',    msg:'Dire wolves have settlements but resist the concept of cities — concentrated, sedentary populations that gradually lose their relationship with the surrounding territory. From a pack survival perspective, a city is a vulnerability: a fixed location that cannot move, surrounded by land that becomes unfamiliar. The debate about whether to build cities is the central political argument in dire wolf society. It has been going for two hundred years.' },
    { id:'dire_wolf_24', title:'Reading the Land',          msg:'Dire wolves read landscape the way scholars read books — for information, for history, for warning. A slope that might look uniform to human eyes tells a dire wolf about drainage patterns, animal movement, seasonal change, and the likely hiding places of ambushes. "The land is speaking," a dire wolf ranger once told a lost human expedition. "You simply haven\'t learned to listen."' },
    { id:'dire_wolf_25', title:'What Makes a Pack',         msg:'"A pack is not a group of individuals who happen to run together. A pack is a decision — made over and over, every day, to choose each other. To be accountable to each other. To notice when someone is struggling. To wait when someone falls behind. We are not strong because we are fast or fierce. We are strong because we do not leave anyone behind."' },
  ],

};

module.exports = LORE;
